In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Created");
    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Activated");
    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Deactivated");
    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Stopped");
    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Resumed");
    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Destroying");
    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("Window Backgrounding");

    return window;
}
```

**Event flow by platform:**

| Transition | iOS/Android | Windows/Mac |
|---|---|---|
| App launch | Created → Activated | Created → Activated |
| Backgrounded | Deactivated → Stopped | Deactivated |
| Foregrounded | Resumed → Activated | Activated |
| Closed | Stopped → Destroying | Destroying |

- **`Backgrounding`** is iOS-only — use it to save state (the `BackgroundingEventArgs` provides a `State` dictionary that is restored on next launch).
- **`Stopped`** won't fire on desktop platforms when the window is simply minimised; it maps to mobile "background" semantics.

Replace `Debug.WriteLine` with your `ILogger` or any sink you prefer.
